{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-archive-js","path":"/2016/universal-inclusive-design-accessibility/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>For this article, I'm going to take a look at the principles of universal design,\nor inclusive design as it's more commonly known, and how it and accessibility\ncan be applied to the current website in my final designs.</p>\n<h2 id=\"universal-design\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#universal-design\" aria-label=\"universal design permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Universal design</h2>\n<p>The Center for Universal Design describes the concept as follows:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The design of products and environments to be usable by all people, to the\ngreatest extent possible, without the need for adaptation or specialised\ndesign</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>What this is saying is that the design of all products and environments should\nbe agnostic and usable to the ability of all people, regardless of disabilities,\nwithout any assistance.</p>\n<p>By constantly planning and incorporating accessibility into your designs, it's\npossible to develop an interface that's accessible to all abilities and that\nprovides the best experience across all technologies, including those that are\nassistive (Miller, 2016).</p>\n<p>By incorporating accessibility into a product's designs, it ultimately reaches\nmore of any organisation's audience. You would think it would be in their best\ninterest to take this on board, but in my experiences this isn't always the\ncase!</p>\n<p>Below I've outlined some of the principles defined by the Center for Universal\nDesign (1997) with regards to the current website, and provided recommendations\nfor how these can be improved and implemented in my designs going forward.</p>\n<h3 id=\"equitable-use\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#equitable-use\" aria-label=\"equitable use permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Equitable Use</h3>\n<p>Equitable use is concerned with ensuring a design is both useful and marketable\nto people with diverse abilities. It's guidelines are as follows:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li>1a. Provide the same means of use for all users: identical whenever possible;\nequivalent when not</li>\n<li>1b. Avoid segregating or stigmatising any users</li>\n<li>1c. Provisions for privacy, security, and safety should be equally available\nto all users</li>\n<li>1d. Make the design appealing to all users</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Currently <a href=\"https://www.tickets.ie\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Tickets.ie</a> has a very limited colour palette\n(Numerous levels of grey and orange) which may not drastically affect users with\ncolour blindness. If we invert the colours, we can also see that it performs for\nthose sensitive to brightness, and easier to distinguish for those suffering\nfrom colour blindness:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 650px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/3c59f4d73b1d12045b891a8211dfb73d/d9ed5/Tickets.ie_Equitable-Use.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 55.21472392638037%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Equitable Use - Problem\"\n        title=\"Equitable Use - Problem\"\n        src=\"/static/3c59f4d73b1d12045b891a8211dfb73d/a6d36/Tickets.ie_Equitable-Use.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/3c59f4d73b1d12045b891a8211dfb73d/222b7/Tickets.ie_Equitable-Use.png 163w,\n/static/3c59f4d73b1d12045b891a8211dfb73d/ff46a/Tickets.ie_Equitable-Use.png 325w,\n/static/3c59f4d73b1d12045b891a8211dfb73d/a6d36/Tickets.ie_Equitable-Use.png 650w,\n/static/3c59f4d73b1d12045b891a8211dfb73d/e548f/Tickets.ie_Equitable-Use.png 975w,\n/static/3c59f4d73b1d12045b891a8211dfb73d/3c492/Tickets.ie_Equitable-Use.png 1300w,\n/static/3c59f4d73b1d12045b891a8211dfb73d/d9ed5/Tickets.ie_Equitable-Use.png 2880w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<figcaption>Equitable Use - Problem</figcaption>\n<p>The most apparent issue lies in the distinguishability of links from other copy\non the website, although the persistent monochromatic tones may render certain\naspects of the website indistinguishable from others.</p>\n<p>We can see how <a href=\"http://www.yelp.com/dublin\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Yelp</a> have accommodated for those\nwith deuteranopia, a common form of colour blindness, by integrating a limited\nbut effective colour palette to differentiate between different sections and\nnavigation elements.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 650px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/d8fc20ed4098aaab663cc3710b7904ad/d9ed5/Yelp_Equitable-Use.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 55.21472392638037%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Equitable Use - Solution\"\n        title=\"Equitable Use - Solution\"\n        src=\"/static/d8fc20ed4098aaab663cc3710b7904ad/a6d36/Yelp_Equitable-Use.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/d8fc20ed4098aaab663cc3710b7904ad/222b7/Yelp_Equitable-Use.png 163w,\n/static/d8fc20ed4098aaab663cc3710b7904ad/ff46a/Yelp_Equitable-Use.png 325w,\n/static/d8fc20ed4098aaab663cc3710b7904ad/a6d36/Yelp_Equitable-Use.png 650w,\n/static/d8fc20ed4098aaab663cc3710b7904ad/e548f/Yelp_Equitable-Use.png 975w,\n/static/d8fc20ed4098aaab663cc3710b7904ad/3c492/Yelp_Equitable-Use.png 1300w,\n/static/d8fc20ed4098aaab663cc3710b7904ad/d9ed5/Yelp_Equitable-Use.png 2880w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<figcaption>Equitable Use - Solution</figcaption>\n<p>The final design will address the above issues by providing clear\ndifferentiation between navigation and copy through the use of type, the\nassistance of iconography, and the use of contrasting colours to differentiate\nseparate sections.</p>\n<h3 id=\"flexibility-in-use\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#flexibility-in-use\" aria-label=\"flexibility in use permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Flexibility in Use</h3>\n<p>Flexibility in use refers to a design accommodating a a wide range of individual\npreferences and abilities. The recommended guidelines for this context are:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li>2a. Provide choice in methods of use</li>\n<li>2b. Accommodate right or left-handed access and use</li>\n<li>2c. Facilitate the user's accuracy and precision</li>\n<li>2d. Provide adaptability to the user's pace</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Tickets.ie in it's current form, doesn't provide a whole lot of flexibility in\nterms of filtering down or sorting search results:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 479px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/991d58cf8e311cb1cb50e3db6c5da5a9/a9b70/Tickets.ie.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 107.97546012269939%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Flexibility in Use\"\n        title=\"Flexibility in Use\"\n        src=\"/static/991d58cf8e311cb1cb50e3db6c5da5a9/a9b70/Tickets.ie.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/991d58cf8e311cb1cb50e3db6c5da5a9/222b7/Tickets.ie.png 163w,\n/static/991d58cf8e311cb1cb50e3db6c5da5a9/ff46a/Tickets.ie.png 325w,\n/static/991d58cf8e311cb1cb50e3db6c5da5a9/a9b70/Tickets.ie.png 479w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 479px) 100vw, 479px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<figcaption>Flexibility in Use - Problem</figcaption>\n<p>Providing flexibile filtering controls would allow the target audience choice in\nthe methods they use, and pivot easily within their context at their own pace.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 650px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/d589058cb9391f303a2bd04295d6eeb0/d2602/Flexibility-in-Use.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 74.84662576687117%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Flexibility in Use\"\n        title=\"Flexibility in Use\"\n        src=\"/static/d589058cb9391f303a2bd04295d6eeb0/6aca1/Flexibility-in-Use.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/d589058cb9391f303a2bd04295d6eeb0/d2f63/Flexibility-in-Use.jpg 163w,\n/static/d589058cb9391f303a2bd04295d6eeb0/c989d/Flexibility-in-Use.jpg 325w,\n/static/d589058cb9391f303a2bd04295d6eeb0/6aca1/Flexibility-in-Use.jpg 650w,\n/static/d589058cb9391f303a2bd04295d6eeb0/7c09c/Flexibility-in-Use.jpg 975w,\n/static/d589058cb9391f303a2bd04295d6eeb0/01ab0/Flexibility-in-Use.jpg 1300w,\n/static/d589058cb9391f303a2bd04295d6eeb0/d2602/Flexibility-in-Use.jpg 4032w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<figcaption>Flexibility in Use - Solution</figcaption>\n<h3 id=\"simple-and-intuitive-use\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#simple-and-intuitive-use\" aria-label=\"simple and intuitive use permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Simple and Intuitive Use</h3>\n<p>It's also important that a design is easy to understand, regardless of the\nuser's experience or knowledge:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li>3a. Eliminate unnecessary complexity</li>\n<li>3b. Be consistent with user expectations and intuition</li>\n<li>3c. Accommodate a wide range of literacy and language skills</li>\n<li>3d. Arrange information consistent with its importance</li>\n<li>3e. Provide effective prompting and feedback during and after task completion</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The current website, as discussed in previous articles, operates in a funnel, and\nhas appalling navigation between artists, events, and venues, a standard of\nwhich any web user expects today.</p>\n<p>As addressed in my article on\n<a href=\"/2016/3/27/information-architecture-content-strategy#information-architecture\">information architecture and content strategy</a>,\nit's intended that the target audience will be able to manipulate the event\nlistings purely by toggling on and off options of their choice, and users should\nbe able to freely navigate between artists, events, and venues without getting\ntrapped.</p>\n<h3 id=\"size-and-space-for-approach-and-use\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#size-and-space-for-approach-and-use\" aria-label=\"size and space for approach and use permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Size and Space for Approach and Use</h3>\n<p>The final principle is concerned with providing appropriate size and space when\nusing a product, regardless of a user's body size, posture, or mobility:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li>7a. Provide a clear line of sight to important elements for any seated or\nstanding user</li>\n<li>7b. Make reach to all components comfortable for any seated or standing user</li>\n<li>7c. Accommodate variations in hand and grip size</li>\n<li>7d. Provide adequate space for the use of assistive devices or personal\nassistance</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The current Tickets.ie website is not optimised for mobile use, so therefore can\nbe tricky to navigate while on a smartphone - the target audience would have to\njump through hoops to view anything on the website, in particular pinching to\nzoom to access individual elements on the page and any specific controls or\nfunctionality.</p>\n<p>Regardless of left or right-handed users, any task would be difficult to\nachieve:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 620px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/6afa93121e47cb54d59494279dc9e422/2a195/Tickets.ie_Size-Space-Approach-Use.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 77.30061349693251%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Size and Space for Approach and Use - Problem\"\n        title=\"Size and Space for Approach and Use - Problem\"\n        src=\"/static/6afa93121e47cb54d59494279dc9e422/2a195/Tickets.ie_Size-Space-Approach-Use.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/6afa93121e47cb54d59494279dc9e422/222b7/Tickets.ie_Size-Space-Approach-Use.png 163w,\n/static/6afa93121e47cb54d59494279dc9e422/ff46a/Tickets.ie_Size-Space-Approach-Use.png 325w,\n/static/6afa93121e47cb54d59494279dc9e422/2a195/Tickets.ie_Size-Space-Approach-Use.png 620w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<figcaption>Size and Space for Approach and Use - Problem</figcaption>\n<p>In an effort to minimise fatigue for the current website on mobile, I've drafted\na quick solution below:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 650px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/4802a69b2a7e63dbb890dc474bc4d902/d2602/Size-Space-Approach-Use.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 74.84662576687117%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Size and Space for Approach and Use - Solution\"\n        title=\"Size and Space for Approach and Use - Solution\"\n        src=\"/static/4802a69b2a7e63dbb890dc474bc4d902/6aca1/Size-Space-Approach-Use.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/4802a69b2a7e63dbb890dc474bc4d902/d2f63/Size-Space-Approach-Use.jpg 163w,\n/static/4802a69b2a7e63dbb890dc474bc4d902/c989d/Size-Space-Approach-Use.jpg 325w,\n/static/4802a69b2a7e63dbb890dc474bc4d902/6aca1/Size-Space-Approach-Use.jpg 650w,\n/static/4802a69b2a7e63dbb890dc474bc4d902/7c09c/Size-Space-Approach-Use.jpg 975w,\n/static/4802a69b2a7e63dbb890dc474bc4d902/01ab0/Size-Space-Approach-Use.jpg 1300w,\n/static/4802a69b2a7e63dbb890dc474bc4d902/d2602/Size-Space-Approach-Use.jpg 4032w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<figcaption>Size and Space for Approach and Use - Solution</figcaption>\n<p>Key actions such as filtering and searching appear towards the bottom of the\nscreen closer to the user, as floating action buttons - if these were located at\nthe top of the screen, it may be hard to reach depending on whether you're left\nor right-handed.</p>\n<p>Switching between views would appear under the section's header as tabbed\nnavigation - While this requires some effort, it's not completely out of reach\nfor either handed individual.</p>\n<p>Finally, the events for selection are displayed as cards in a descending,\nscrollable list - this is more than suitable for anyone to manipulate and select\nthe item they require.</p>\n<p>Now that I've addressed how some of the principles of universal design can be\napplied to my designs, I'll speak briefly about accessibility and how it can be\nconsidered in any web application.</p>\n<h2 id=\"accessibility\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#accessibility\" aria-label=\"accessibility permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Accessibility</h2>\n<p>To develop a modern software application that integrates advanced user interface\ncontrols and dynamic content, that's effectively accessible to users who rely on\nassistive technology such as screen readers,\n<a href=\"https://www.w3.org/WAI/intro/aria\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Accessible Rich Internet Applications Suite (WAI-ARIA)</a>\nis employed (Cooper, 2016).</p>\n<p>To meet the criteria for accessibility standards, the current website was\nscanned using an accessibility policy tester, against a number of guidelines:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 650px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/1773cd7cbd5baf3366909436012a8875/d9ed5/Tickets.ie_Policy-testing.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 55.21472392638037%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Accessibility policy testing\"\n        title=\"Accessibility policy testing\"\n        src=\"/static/1773cd7cbd5baf3366909436012a8875/a6d36/Tickets.ie_Policy-testing.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/1773cd7cbd5baf3366909436012a8875/222b7/Tickets.ie_Policy-testing.png 163w,\n/static/1773cd7cbd5baf3366909436012a8875/ff46a/Tickets.ie_Policy-testing.png 325w,\n/static/1773cd7cbd5baf3366909436012a8875/a6d36/Tickets.ie_Policy-testing.png 650w,\n/static/1773cd7cbd5baf3366909436012a8875/e548f/Tickets.ie_Policy-testing.png 975w,\n/static/1773cd7cbd5baf3366909436012a8875/3c492/Tickets.ie_Policy-testing.png 1300w,\n/static/1773cd7cbd5baf3366909436012a8875/d9ed5/Tickets.ie_Policy-testing.png 2880w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<figcaption>Accessibility policy testing</figcaption>\n<p>The results were astonishing - On one section of the website, there were <strong>113\nviolations</strong> alone! These varied from severe violations like how the structure\nof certain elements on the page would prevent screen readers from navigating\nsuccessfully throughout the content, to missing significant attributes on media\nand navigation elements that provide screen readers with valuable content\ndescriptions for those with visual impairments.</p>\n<p>If you’re not suffering from a colour vision deficiency, it can be pretty hard\nto imagine what it looks like to be colour blind. Visual impairments can vary in\nseverity, from colour vision deficiency which prevents those that live with it\nto identify change in colour (Miller, 2016), to those who can't discern any\ncontent, and rely on screen readers as their main interface with an application.</p>\n<p>While my final prototype will show a proof-of-concept and not go as far as fully\nengineering the application, below are a number of recommendations I've\nsuggested for improvement:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li>Text alternatives should be provided for any non-text content</li>\n<li>Ensure semantic HTML document structure is provided to allow screen readers\nnavigate naturally throughout the document</li>\n<li>Make the contrast between colour of text and it's background distinguishable\nand legible</li>\n</ul>\n<p>With the last of considerations aside, I can continue with the design production\nprocess and finally start building!</p>\n<h2 id=\"next-steps\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#next-steps\" aria-label=\"next steps permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Next steps</h2>\n<p>My final article will detail the production process of my design and prototype\nusing Adobe Illustrator and Experience Design - I'll walk through the typical\nflow for Eoin, our primary user, and incorporate all of the artifacts I've\nproduced so far.</p>\n<p>I'll also discuss the usability test I conducted to evaluate the prototype's\ndesign, along with any materials produced.</p>\n<h2 id=\"references\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#references\" aria-label=\"references permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>References</h2>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li>Cooper, M. (2016). <em>WAI-ARIA Overview</em>. Retrieved April 4, 2016, from\n<a href=\"https://www.w3.org/WAI/intro/aria\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">https://www.w3.org/WAI/intro/aria</a></li>\n<li>Miller, M.E. (2016). <em>Top Ten Inclusive Design Lessons</em>. Retrieved April 4,\n2016, from\n<a href=\"http://ageandability.com/2016/01/14/top-ten-inclusive-design-lessons/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">http://ageandability.com/2016/01/14/top-ten-inclusive-design-lessons/</a></li>\n<li>The Center for Universal Design (1997). <em>The Principles of Universal Design</em>\n(Version 2.0). NC State University.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"resources\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#resources\" aria-label=\"resources permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Resources</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=1utChefMxn10Ti0ZI8Zm61DvWHg8naaMcKg\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Flexibility in Use</a></p>","frontmatter":{"date":"10 April, 2016","title":"Universal (inclusive) design and accessibility"}}},"pageContext":{"previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/2016/cognitive-social-psychology/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Cognitive and social psychology"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/2016/high-fidelity-solution/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"High-fidelity solution"}},"slug":"/2016/universal-inclusive-design-accessibility/"}}}